Paid Notice: Memorials  SIMON, FLORENCE ROSLYN CHARWAT OF NEW YORK CITY PASSED AWAY PEACEFULLY SUNDAY, AUGUST 16TH. A NATIVE NEW YORKER, SHE WOULD HAVE CELEBRATED HER 90TH BIRTHDAY ON OCTOBER 2ND. SHE WAS THE DAUGHTER OF EVELYN BONHART CHARWAT NEWMAN AND WILLIAM CHARWAT, AND NIECE OF CELIA BERNSTEIN GREENFIELD, GODDAUGHTER AND NIECE OF FREDERICK WILLIAM GREENFIELD, AND NIECE OF DORIS KLEIN. FLORENCE ATTENDED P.S. 6 AND JULIA RICHMOND HIGH SCHOOL BEFORE GRADUATING FROM GREAT NECK HIGH SCHOOL AND ROCKLAND COMMUNITY COLLEGE. DURING WORLD WAR II SHE WORKED FOR THE FBI IN WASHINGTON, DC AND LATER WORKED FOR THE FEDERAL SECURITY AGENCY IN NEW YORK CITY. WHILE RAISING HER FAMILY, SHE TAUGHT AND ADMINISTERED SEVERAL PRE, SCHOOLS IN WESTCHESTER, ROCKLAND AND BERGEN COUNTIES. FLORENCE TRAVELED EXTENSIVELY, CAMPING ACROSS THE UNITED STATES AND EUROPE WITH HER FAMILY IN THE 1960S. SHE LIVED IN SEVERAL LATIN AMERICAN COUNTRIES, AND LATER TRAVELED THROUGH MOST OTHER PARTS OF THE WORLD. A DEVOTED MEMBER OF THE BRANDEIS UNIVERSITY NATIONAL WOMEN'S COMMITTEE FOR OVER 50 YEARS, FLORENCE SERVED AS PRESIDENT OF SEVERAL OF ITS CHAPTERS, AS A MEMBER OF ITS NATIONAL BOARD OF DIRECTORS, AND ROSE TO BE A PRESIDENT'S COUNCILOR. SHE ALSO WAS A PAST PRESIDENT OF THE NEW YORK CITY OPERA GUILD AND AN ACTIVE MEMBER OF THE NEW YORK PHILHARMONIC VOLUNTEERS AND ITS HERITAGE SOCIETY. FLORENCE IS SURVIVED BY HER CHILDREN WENDY SIMON ZLOTLOW (MARK ZLOTLOW), MICHAEL SIMON, AND BARBARA ANN SIMON (EZRA TEITELBAUM), AND FORMER HUSBAND MURRAY SIMON. SHE WAS THE BELOVED GRANDMOTHER OF JOSHUA ZLOTLOW (BETINA LEVEAU) AND DAVID ZLOTLOW (SANDRA GALLARDO), AND ADORING GREAT, GRANDMOTHER OF MARCELO ALEJANDRO ZLOTLOW, AND BELOVED SISTER OF ARTHUR CHARWAT (MARILYN YANIS). THE FUNERAL WILL TAKE PLACE ON WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 19TH AT PLAZA JEWISH COMMUNITY CHAPEL, 630 AMSTERDAM AVENUE AT WEST 91ST STREET AT 11:00AM. 1

Paid Notice: Memorials  SIMON, FLORENCE ROSLYN CHARWAT OF NEW YORK CITY PASSED AWAY PEACEFULLY SUNDAY, AUGUST 16TH. A NATIVE NEW YORKER, SHE WOULD HAVE CELEBRATED HER 90TH BIRTHDAY ON OCTOBER 2ND. SHE WAS THE DAUGHTER OF EVELYN BONHART CHARWAT NEWMAN AND WILLIAM CHARWAT, AND NIECE OF CELIA BERNSTEIN GREENFIELD, GODDAUGHTER AND NIECE OF FREDERICK WILLIAM GREENFIELD, AND NIECE OF DORIS KLEIN. FLORENCE ATTENDED P.S. 6 AND JULIA RICHMOND HIGH SCHOOL BEFORE GRADUATING FROM GREAT NECK HIGH SCHOOL AND ROCKLAND COMMUNITY COLLEGE. DURING WORLD WAR II SHE WORKED FOR THE FBI IN WASHINGTON, DC AND LATER WORKED FOR THE FEDERAL SECURITY AGENCY IN NEW YORK CITY. WHILE RAISING HER FAMILY, SHE TAUGHT AND ADMINISTERED SEVERAL PRE, SCHOOLS IN WESTCHESTER, ROCKLAND AND BERGEN COUNTIES. FLORENCE TRAVELED EXTENSIVELY, CAMPING ACROSS THE UNITED STATES AND EUROPE WITH HER FAMILY IN THE 1960S. SHE LIVED IN SEVERAL LATIN AMERICAN COUNTRIES, AND LATER TRAVELED THROUGH MOST OTHER PARTS OF THE WORLD. A DEVOTED MEMBER OF THE BRANDEIS UNIVERSITY NATIONAL WOMEN'S COMMITTEE FOR OVER 50 YEARS, FLORENCE SERVED AS PRESIDENT OF SEVERAL OF ITS CHAPTERS, AS A MEMBER OF ITS NATIONAL BOARD OF DIRECTORS, AND ROSE TO BE A PRESIDENT'S COUNCILOR. SHE ALSO WAS A PAST PRESIDENT OF THE NEW YORK CITY OPERA GUILD AND AN ACTIVE MEMBER OF THE NEW YORK PHILHARMONIC VOLUNTEERS AND ITS HERITAGE SOCIETY. FLORENCE IS SURVIVED BY HER CHILDREN WENDY SIMON ZLOTLOW (MARK ZLOTLOW), MICHAEL SIMON, AND BARBARA ANN SIMON (EZRA TEITELBAUM), AND FORMER HUSBAND MURRAY SIMON. SHE WAS THE BELOVED GRANDMOTHER OF JOSHUA ZLOTLOW (BETINA LEVEAU) AND DAVID ZLOTLOW (SANDRA GALLARDO), AND ADORING GREAT, GRANDMOTHER OF MARCELO ALEJANDRO ZLOTLOW, AND BELOVED SISTER OF ARTHUR CHARWAT (MARILYN YANIS). THE FUNERAL WILL TAKE PLACE ON WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 19TH AT PLAZA JEWISH COMMUNITY CHAPEL, 630 AMSTERDAM AVENUE AT WEST 91ST STREET AT 11:00AM. 1

Paid Notice: Memorials  BINGHAM, W. RICHARD "DICK." DIED PEACEFULLY AT HIS CHERISHED HOME IN FISHERS ISLAND, NY ON AUGUST 18TH SURROUNDED BY HIS LOVING FAMILY. THE LOSS IS FELT FOR THIS FAMILY MAN WHO WAS A LIFETIME KEEN INTELLECT, NAVY VETERAN, RESPECTED FINANCIER, PHILANTHROPIST, CIVIC AFFAIRS STRATEGIST, COMPETITOR AND AVID SPORTSMAN. HE WAS FOREMOST A LOVING HUSBAND AND FATHER DEDICATED TO HIS EXTENDED FAMILY AND FRIENDS AND HAVING AS HE CALLED IT "THE FORTUNATE OPPORTUNITY TO EXPERIENCE A LIFETIME OF PARTICIPATION IN PROBLEM SOLVING AND CREATION OF NEW ENTITIES." DICK WAS BORN IN NEW YORK CITY AND GREW UP IN BUCKS COUNTY, PA AND HILLSBOROUGH, CA. HE ATTENDED HILLSBOROUGH SCHOOL, TOWN SCHOOL FOR BOYS (CLASS OF '49), MIDDLESEX (CLASS OF '53), STANFORD UNIVERSITY (CLASS OF '57), AND HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL (CLASS OF '61). HE ATTENDED THE UNIVERSITIES OF GENEVA AND PARIS. THROUGHOUT EVERY STAGE OF HIS LIFE HE HELD A MYRIAD OF LEADERSHIP POSITIONS BEGINNING AT STANFORD WHERE HE WAS PRESIDENT OF PHI DELTA THETA FRATERNITY, AND HEAD OF CAMPUS SECURITY. HE SERVED AS LINE OFFICER ABOARD THE U.S. NAVY DESTROYER, U.S.S. DAVIS, FROM 1957, 1959. HE REMEMBERED HIS NAVAL SERVICE FONDLY WHICH CONTRIBUTED TO HIS UNWAVERING LOVE OF THE OCEAN. DICK WAS CHARACTERIZED BY AND OFTEN CLOSED REMARKS ON OCCASION WITH THIS LINE TAKEN FROM HIS US NAVY DAYS, "MAY FAIR WINDS AND FOLLOWING SEAS ACCOMPANY YOU." FOLLOWING HIS MILITARY SERVICE, DICK BEGAN HIS CAREER ON WALL STREET AT THE INVESTMENT BANKING FIRM OF KUHN, LOEB, AND CO. IN 1961. AS A PARTNER, DIRECTOR OF INVESTMENT BANKING, A MEMBER OF THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE AND BOARD OF DIRECTORS, HE ADVISED MANY COMPANIES AND COUNTRIES ON CAPITAL RAISING ACTIVITIES. HE CONTINUED HIS CAREER AS A PARTNER OF LEHMAN BROTHERS IN 1977 WHERE HE WAS DIRECTOR OF INVESTMENT BANKING, CORPORATE FINANCE, AND MERGERS AND ACQUISITIONS AND A MEMBER OF THE BOARD. IN 1988 HE FOUNDED AMERICAN INDUSTRIAL PARTNERS (AIP) WHICH BECAME A RESPECTED, GROUND, BREAKING PRIVATE EQUITY FIRM. AS A SAVVY INVESTOR AND PRESIDENT OF AIP, DICK AND HIS AMERICAN INDUSTRIAL PARTNERS TEAM RAISED FOUR FUNDS AND LED MULTIPLE INVESTMENTS IN DIVERSE INDUSTRIAL COMPANIES WHILE HE SERVED ON A NUMBER OF CORPORATE BOARDS. IN 1996, DURING MAYOR FRANK JORDAN'S ADMINISTRATION IN SAN FRANCISCO, DICK WAS APPOINTED HONORARY CONSUL TO THE REPUBLIC OF LITHUANIA. ALSO, DURING THAT TIME, HE WAS APPOINTED TO THE NEWLY FORMED SAN FRANCISCO'S COMMITTEE ON JOBS WHERE THE PRIMARY FOCUS WAS TO PROMOTE A BUSINESS CLIMATE THAT ALLOWED SAN FRANCISCO TO REMAIN A DESIRABLE PLACE TO LIVE, WORK, AND OPERATE A BUSINESS. THROUGHOUT HIS LIFE, DICK WAS DEDICATED TO PHILANTHROPY AND OFFERED HIS SERVICES AND SUPPORT TO MANY BAY AREA INSTITUTIONS OVER THE YEARS. HIS PHILANTHROPIC INTERESTS REFLECTED HIS LOVE OF THE WONDERS OF THE WORLD, NATURE, THE OCEAN, MUSIC, AND THE ARTS. HIS MOST MEMORABLE PHILANTHROPIC LIFETIME ACHIEVEMENT WAS THE CALIFORNIA ACADEMY OF SCIENCES LOCATED IN GOLDEN GATE PARK, SAN FRANCISCO. HE SERVED AS CHAIRMAN OF ITS BOARD FROM 1996 UNTIL IT'S REOPENING IN 2007. HE WAS EXTREMELY PROUD OF WHAT HE AND THE BOARD ACCOMPLISHED, ESPECIALLY LITERALLY KNOCKING ON DOORS TO AID IN THE PASSING OF PROPOSITION B, WHICH WAS PIVOTAL IN THE PROCESS TO COMPLETELY REBUILD THE ACADEMY INTO THE WORLD, CLASS SCIENCE AND EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION THAT IT IS TODAY. AS AN ADJUNCT TO THE ACADEMY, HE ENVISIONED AND WORKED TIRELESSLY TO RAISE PRIVATE MONIES NEEDED TO FUND THE MUSIC CONCOURSE GARAGE WHICH LIES BETWEEN THE ACADEMY AND DE YOUNG MUSEUMS. HE SERVED AS CHAIRMAN OF THAT BOARD. HE PASSIONATELY BELIEVED THAT EDUCATION AND EDUCATIONAL PURSUITS WERE IMPORTANT FOR INDIVIDUALS AND SOCIETY. TO HIM, SAVING AND REBUILDING THE ACADEMY WAS THE TANGIBLE APEX OF THAT PASSION. HIS EFFORTS HELPED ENSURE THE ACADEMY REMAINED IN GOLDEN GATE PARK AS A STATE, OF, THE, ART LEARNING CENTER AND MUSEUM. DICK ALSO IS PAST TRUSTEE OF THE TOWN SCHOOL FOR BOYS, MARIN COUNTRY DAY SCHOOL, THE URBAN SCHOOL, THE BAY SCHOOL, MIDDLESEX SCHOOL, THE WORLD AFFAIRS COUNCIL, ST JOHNS CHURCH ON FISHER'S ISLAND, AND CPMC FOUNDATION. HE WAS A MEMBER OF THE PACIFIC UNION CLUB, THE BURLINGAME COUNTRY CLUB, THE SAN FRANCISCO GOLF CLUB, AND THE FISHER'S ISLAND CLUB. DICK IS SURVIVED BY HIS LOVING WIFE, WENDY WASSON BINGHAM, ADORING CHILDREN, LOCK, FRANCES, AND GRACE BINGHAM, AND DEVOTED SISTER BETSY BINGHAM DAVIS. IN LIEU OF FLOWERS, THE FAMILY REQUESTS THAT DONATIONS BE MADE IN DICK'S MEMORY TO THE CALIFORNIA ACADEMY OF SCIENCES, WHICH WAS AN IMPORTANT CAUSE FOR DICK. 1

Paid Notice: Memorials  MELLO, H. JOSEPH "JOE", 73, OF MANHATTAN, DIED SUDDENLY ON AUGUST 19, 2015. BORN IN BROOKLYN, HE WAS THE SON OF THE LATE DOMINIC AND PRUDENCE (BELLANTI) MELLO. MR. MELLO WAS RAISED A PROUD ITALIAN AND WAS ADMIRED FOR HIS UNWAVERING IOVE OF HIS FAMILY. MR. MELLO IS SURVIVED BY HIS BELOVED COUSINS PINA (TOMARCHIO) PERGOLIZZI, PRUDENCE (BELLANTI) MCCAFFERTY, RUSS TOMARCHIO, LOUISE (ALIMENTI) CLARKE, ARLENE (ALIMENTI) ROSICA, MARIE ALIMENTI, LORRAINE (ALIMENTI) SACCHETTI, AS WELL AS MANY OTHER LOVING FAMILY MEMBERS AND FRIENDS. THE CLEAR PATRIARCH OF THE BELLANTI FAMILY, "UNCLE JOE" WAS UNCLE AND GODFATHER TO MORE NIECES AND NEPHEWS THAN CAN BE COUNTED. MR. MELLO SERVED IN THE UNITED STATES ARMY AS A CAPTAIN IN VIETNAM DURING THE TET OFFENSIVE. HE DEVOTED HIS PROFESSIONAL CAREER TO THE LAW. AFTER GRADUATING FROM CORNELL UNIVERSITY IN 1963 AND NEW YORK UNIVERSITY LAW IN 1966, HE WAS ADMITTED TO THE NEW YORK STATE BAR IN 1967. FOR NEARLY HALF A CENTURY, HE PROVIDED CLIENTS COUNSEL ON INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY, COPYRIGHT AND COMMERCIAL LITIGATION ISSUES. HE BEGAN HIS CAREER AND BECAME A PARTNER AT GOLENBOCK AND BARREL LLP AND CONTINUED AS A VALUED PARTNER OF THELEN REID AND PRIEST LLP. MR. MELLO WAS ACTIVE IN THE NEW YORK STATE BAR ASSOCIATION (NYSBA) AND HAD SERVED AS CHAIRPERSON OF THE COPYRIGHT LAW COMMITTEE OF THE INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY SECTION OF THE NYSBA. HE CONCLUDED HIS CAREER AT WINSTON AND STRAWN LLP, RETIRING IN 2011 AND SINCE THEN REMAINING IN SERVICE OF COUNSEL. A MAN WHO LOVED TO GATHER AT A TABLE WITH FAMILY AND FRIENDS, JOE WAS A CONNOISSEUR OF FOOD AND WINE AND AN AFICIONADO OF CONVERSATION, FAMOUS FOR PASSING ON FAMILY HISTORY THROUGH WONDERFUL STORYTELLING. EACH DAY, HE RELISHED HIS NEW YORK TIMES AND TOOK GREAT JOY IN DISCUSSING ALL THE NEWS. HE LOVED TO TRAVEL, OFTEN WITH HIS DEAR FRIENDS FROM CORNELL UNIVERSITY, AND ESPECIALLY TO HIS ANCESTRAL HOME OF SICILY, WHICH WAS NEVER FAR FROM HIS HEART. HE WILL BE GREATLY MISSED BY HIS FAMILY AND FRIENDS AND WILL BE REMEMBERED FOREVER BY THOSE WHO HAD THE PRIVILEGE TO KNOW HIM. FAMILY AND FRIENDS MAY VISIT TORREGROSSA FUNERAL HOME, 345 AVENUE U, BROOKLYN, NY ON MONDAY, AUGUST 24, 2015 FROM 2PM, 5PM AND 7PM, 9PM. A MASS OF CHRISTIAN BURIAL WILL BE HELD ON TUESDAY, AUGUST 25, 2015 AT ST. ATHANASIUS CHURCH AT 10:30AM, AT 2154 61ST STREET AND BAY PARKWAY, BROOKLYN, NY. BURIAL TO IMMEDIATELY FOLLOW AT GREENWOOD CEMETERY IN BROOKLYN, NY. IN LIEU OF FLOWERS, DONATIONS CAN BE MADE TO THE "H. JOSEPH MELLO '63 SCHOLARSHIP FUND" AT CORNELL UNIVERSITY IN THE COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCES IN HIS MEMORY. CORNELL UNIVERSITY, P.O. SEX 25842, LEHIGH VAHEY, PA 18003, 9692 OR GO TO WEBSITE: GIVING.COMELL.EDU AND REFER TO "WAYS TO GIVE." 1

Paid Notice: Memorials  BINGHAM, W. RICHARD "DICK." DIED PEACEFULLY AT HIS CHERISHED HOME IN FISHERS ISLAND, NY ON AUGUST 18TH SURROUNDED BY HIS LOVING FAMILY. THE LOSS IS FELT FOR THIS FAMILY MAN WHO WAS A LIFETIME KEEN INTELLECT, NAVY VETERAN, RESPECTED FINANCIER, PHILANTHROPIST, CIVIC AFFAIRS STRATEGIST, COMPETITOR AND AVID SPORTSMAN. HE WAS FOREMOST A LOVING HUSBAND AND FATHER DEDICATED TO HIS EXTENDED FAMILY AND FRIENDS AND HAVING AS HE CALLED IT "THE FORTUNATE OPPORTUNITY TO EXPERIENCE A LIFETIME OF PARTICIPATION IN PROBLEM SOLVING AND CREATION OF NEW ENTITIES." DICK WAS BORN IN NEW YORK CITY AND GREW UP IN BUCKS COUNTY, PA AND HILLSBOROUGH, CA. HE ATTENDED HILLSBOROUGH SCHOOL, TOWN SCHOOL FOR BOYS (CLASS OF '49), MIDDLESEX (CLASS OF '53), STANFORD UNIVERSITY (CLASS OF '57), AND HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL (CLASS OF '61). HE ATTENDED THE UNIVERSITIES OF GENEVA AND PARIS. THROUGHOUT EVERY STAGE OF HIS LIFE HE HELD A MYRIAD OF LEADERSHIP POSITIONS BEGINNING AT STANFORD WHERE HE WAS PRESIDENT OF PHI DELTA THETA FRATERNITY, AND HEAD OF CAMPUS SECURITY. HE SERVED AS LINE OFFICER ABOARD THE U.S. NAVY DESTROYER, U.S.S. DAVIS, FROM 1957, 1959. HE REMEMBERED HIS NAVAL SERVICE FONDLY WHICH CONTRIBUTED TO HIS UNWAVERING LOVE OF THE OCEAN. DICK WAS CHARACTERIZED BY AND OFTEN CLOSED REMARKS ON OCCASION WITH THIS LINE TAKEN FROM HIS US NAVY DAYS, "MAY FAIR WINDS AND FOLLOWING SEAS ACCOMPANY YOU." FOLLOWING HIS MILITARY SERVICE, DICK BEGAN HIS CAREER ON WALL STREET AT THE INVESTMENT BANKING FIRM OF KUHN, LOEB, AND CO. IN 1961. AS A PARTNER, DIRECTOR OF INVESTMENT BANKING, A MEMBER OF THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE AND BOARD OF DIRECTORS, HE ADVISED MANY COMPANIES AND COUNTRIES ON CAPITAL RAISING ACTIVITIES. HE CONTINUED HIS CAREER AS A PARTNER OF LEHMAN BROTHERS IN 1977 WHERE HE WAS DIRECTOR OF INVESTMENT BANKING, CORPORATE FINANCE, AND MERGERS AND ACQUISITIONS AND A MEMBER OF THE BOARD. IN 1988 HE FOUNDED AMERICAN INDUSTRIAL PARTNERS (AIP) WHICH BECAME A RESPECTED, GROUND, BREAKING PRIVATE EQUITY FIRM. AS A SAVVY INVESTOR AND PRESIDENT OF AIP, DICK AND HIS AMERICAN INDUSTRIAL PARTNERS TEAM RAISED FOUR FUNDS AND LED MULTIPLE INVESTMENTS IN DIVERSE INDUSTRIAL COMPANIES WHILE HE SERVED ON A NUMBER OF CORPORATE BOARDS. IN 1996, DURING MAYOR FRANK JORDAN'S ADMINISTRATION IN SAN FRANCISCO, DICK WAS APPOINTED HONORARY CONSUL TO THE REPUBLIC OF LITHUANIA. ALSO, DURING THAT TIME, HE WAS APPOINTED TO THE NEWLY FORMED SAN FRANCISCO'S COMMITTEE ON JOBS WHERE THE PRIMARY FOCUS WAS TO PROMOTE A BUSINESS CLIMATE THAT ALLOWED SAN FRANCISCO TO REMAIN A DESIRABLE PLACE TO LIVE, WORK, AND OPERATE A BUSINESS. THROUGHOUT HIS LIFE, DICK WAS DEDICATED TO PHILANTHROPY AND OFFERED HIS SERVICES AND SUPPORT TO MANY BAY AREA INSTITUTIONS OVER THE YEARS. HIS PHILANTHROPIC INTERESTS REFLECTED HIS LOVE OF THE WONDERS OF THE WORLD, NATURE, THE OCEAN, MUSIC, AND THE ARTS. HIS MOST MEMORABLE PHILANTHROPIC LIFETIME ACHIEVEMENT WAS THE CALIFORNIA ACADEMY OF SCIENCES LOCATED IN GOLDEN GATE PARK, SAN FRANCISCO. HE SERVED AS CHAIRMAN OF ITS BOARD FROM 1996 UNTIL IT'S REOPENING IN 2007. HE WAS EXTREMELY PROUD OF WHAT HE AND THE BOARD ACCOMPLISHED, ESPECIALLY LITERALLY KNOCKING ON DOORS TO AID IN THE PASSING OF PROPOSITION B, WHICH WAS PIVOTAL IN THE PROCESS TO COMPLETELY REBUILD THE ACADEMY INTO THE WORLD, CLASS SCIENCE AND EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTION THAT IT IS TODAY. AS AN ADJUNCT TO THE ACADEMY, HE ENVISIONED AND WORKED TIRELESSLY TO RAISE PRIVATE MONIES NEEDED TO FUND THE MUSIC CONCOURSE GARAGE WHICH LIES BETWEEN THE ACADEMY AND DE YOUNG MUSEUMS. HE SERVED AS CHAIRMAN OF THAT BOARD. HE PASSIONATELY BELIEVED THAT EDUCATION AND EDUCATIONAL PURSUITS WERE IMPORTANT FOR INDIVIDUALS AND SOCIETY. TO HIM, SAVING AND REBUILDING THE ACADEMY WAS THE TANGIBLE APEX OF THAT PASSION. HIS EFFORTS HELPED ENSURE THE ACADEMY REMAINED IN GOLDEN GATE PARK AS A STATE, OF, THE, ART LEARNING CENTER AND MUSEUM. DICK ALSO IS PAST TRUSTEE OF THE TOWN SCHOOL FOR BOYS, MARIN COUNTRY DAY SCHOOL, THE URBAN SCHOOL, THE BAY SCHOOL, MIDDLESEX SCHOOL, THE WORLD AFFAIRS COUNCIL, ST JOHNS CHURCH ON FISHER'S ISLAND, AND CPMC FOUNDATION. HE WAS A MEMBER OF THE PACIFIC UNION CLUB, THE BURLINGAME COUNTRY CLUB, THE SAN FRANCISCO GOLF CLUB, AND THE FISHER'S ISLAND CLUB. DICK IS SURVIVED BY HIS LOVING WIFE, WENDY WASSON BINGHAM, ADORING CHILDREN, LOCK, FRANCES, AND GRACE BINGHAM, AND DEVOTED SISTER BETSY BINGHAM DAVIS. IN LIEU OF FLOWERS, THE FAMILY REQUESTS THAT DONATIONS BE MADE IN DICK'S MEMORY TO THE CALIFORNIA ACADEMY OF SCIENCES, WHICH WAS AN IMPORTANT CAUSE FOR DICK. 1
